At 20k I could feel that my body was tired. I felt tired a lot more than I wanted to admit in November as well. I did my best, pushed as hard as I could, had 2 puke resets, a short trail nap & I didn't quit 
I never knew my exact placement in the race to include the last 5k. In those last kilometers, I was able to rally past 3 runners into 11th & experienced a crazy sprint at the line to
get 10th, 1st Master & a guaranteed spot into UTMB... by 1 second! 
A strong finish always feels good & I am happy to put a wrap on 2022 🙏

My belief & goals for '22 was podium finishes at the world's best trail ultras in '22: 
@eigerultratrail , @utmbmontblanc & @di_th_by_utmb 

While I was successful at building back from knee surgery & Covid, I missed my big goals.  I also got to explore & race my heart out with no injuries across the world. I got to learn so much & share the journey with David. My knee never hurt or failed me. I was able to learn so much. I saw massive success. I got to believe & I loved it.  I still believe! 

For Thailand by UTMB, I was able to focus more of my energy on training, but I missed the mark chasing volume (103 & 113 mile weeks in November). 
I'm embarrassed that I chose to chase numbers & ignored a better path. I wasn't honest with myself & Coach David on my fatigue. Belief at all costs & stubbornness comes to mind, but on the flip side, I sure had a lot of fun pushing my limits & going all-in. Back in November I  said I would be happy regardless of race results & I am. I'm still making mistakes along with learning more than ever! 

I love the game ❤️

So much JOY! The people, the racing, the wild trails, the food. 
The people 🥇
Thank you Thailand 🇹🇭

This is what it feels & looks like to go from 14th to 10th in the last 5k of a 100k with 20,000ft climbing in Thailand 

You can see 11th. 

I tell my coaching clients I expect them to be savage in the last 90 min of an ultramarathon. 
Slam caffeine & tell the brain that you aren't interested in it's complaining anymore. It's time to go! 
I'm sad to say my race performance sucked in Thailand but I am proud I was savage in the last 90 minutes

I wasn't able to run or even walk without limping 2 weeks before this picture of me racing Thailand by UTMB
  
I had tendonitis & a strain of the adductor magnus of my overused non-surgery leg (right leg). Unfortunately, this was only a symptom of a bigger problem. 

Once I was able to consistently run post-knee surgery, which was over a year ago, I believed I could skip ahead of the recommended PT & just focus on my running(cringe)

I hid behind the idea that doing some bodyweight squats, lunges & step-ups after my run would fix a major post-knee surgery muscle imbalance. I've never had a big injury, I was impatient & I just skipped ahead to dedicating all my energy & focus to training &  running in the mountains

I'm a professional at believing, but when I believe in something stupid, things go really bad. I got so caught up in the next workout, the next long run & the next race. I ignored the fact that my left leg was visibly smaller than my right & that I was hobbled. 
I was stuck for a year in an ugly blindness to the obvious fact that you can't run to your potential with just one strong leg

Three weeks ago I admitted myself to the professional help of Jimmy Picard @redefinephysio. The veil was lifted & I had the well-earned embarrassment of a strength test showing I was 20-30% weaker in my left leg. I earned the honor of "the biggest imbalance I've seen", but just like that I was on the path to balance & done hiding
It is unbelievably bittersweet to have done my fastest 10 x 1 min workouts in at least 3 years after just a few weeks of focused strength work

Massively humbled, but more excited & dedicated than ever to running fast, having fun in the mountains & crushing the competition

I think about UTMB. every. single. day.

At the finish I wasn't thinking about my race, or winning. I was beside myself with gratefulness to have been able to run through Monumet Valley & then experience Navajo culture, hospitality & people. 
I hesitate to share this experience because the event is so small, intimate & not commercialized. I don't want it to change.  These people are proud to have this race & want you to come though & share with them their land & heritage. 
One can't just come run the trails or roads in Monument Valley, it's not ours.  The park was closed & we were gifted the chance to run through this sacred land. At the finish, Navajo people sang, played music, danced, & told stories. They honored the family of a Navajo Code Talker (look it up).

"These trophies aren't worthy of being proud of"
-Me, 1978- 2023

I didn't realize how proud & impressed Felix was of my race this weekend until we got home & he started to ask about some of the trophies stashed around the cabin 

After some looking around Felix told me I should put my  @hardrock100run trophy, 4th at @utmbmontblanc & my Monument Valley 50k trophies where we could see them better

I've resisted putting trophies prominently on display in the cabin because it felt taboo & because I have always felt anxious that I need to & will do far better. A feeling that these trophies were not worthy to show off & that I needed to do far bigger & better things. 
These trophies aren't worthy of being proud of. 

Felix felt & saw that this weekend's Monument Valley 50k was a big win. He knew it wasn't competitive or an incredibly fast time. He knows that I don't consider myself fast or race-fit right now
I'm going to be proud of all three of these trophies right now. 
You can see all three 🏆 on display at the cabin when you come by

The best part is today, every day

11 years as a full-time professional athlete

For a number of these last 11 years, I was fighting to prove to our community, myself & sponsors that I belonged. For some of those 11 years, the wins came easy

This year, I am working as hard or harder than ever & incorporating many different tactics. I'm focusing on tactics I use to be able to ignore. 
I'm doing better at listening to my coach @mountainroche & working with him to dial in an ideal training approach. I'm  working with Jimmy @redefinephysio this year on a specialized strength program. I don't eat food  that obviously sets me back. I absolutely eat enough always.  With few exceptions, I don't drink booze. I drink @athleticgreens & whey protein daily. 
I love the game & commit to it more every year

While my raw speed & recovery is not what it was 11 years ago, I still believe in myself

The process is still so much fun. I'm still in love with the raw beauty & simplicity of running. I'm most happy exploring wild places, experiencing culture, competing against the best in the world, pushing & trying to find my limits! 

While @utmbmontblanc is the big goal this year, the best part is today, every day 💙

social_posts.post_text:
@lakesonoma50 was absolutely beautiful! With a lot of rain this year, the course was very green with incredible wildflowers along the trail. 
Unfortunately, at mile 4 while running fast with the lead pack through the mud, I strained a muscle in my groin/inguinal area. The strain initially didn't affect me as it was fairly mil. I was able to carry on racing, but every mile the strain became more noticeable & started to affect my gait. It became clear that  it would be best for me to drop out & avoid making the slight strain a big injury. I dropped at mile 21 where my awesome crew & coaching client  @tyler_gamlen was waiting. I was in 13th place at that point.  It's always disappointing not to be able run the race, but I had the sweet experience of hanging with Tyler & seeing @richardalexlockwood have an awesome race placing 6th & just 6 minutes from 4th at this crazy competitive race! Rich was also the first guy over 30 in the race! 
So fun to hang with the trail community, see most of this out and back course, see Rich race so well & spend time with great friends. 

Next up: @lavaredoultratrail 80k in June!!! 

My groin is already feeling better 🥳

social_posts.post_text:
This is the least upset I've been after a DNF

I could feel the fitness as I ran with & in the lead pack in the first 10 miles at Saturday's @lakesonoma50 race in Healdsburg. I ran comfortably & efficiently up-hill, & bombed the downhills on muddy trails

I've avoided Lake Sonoma for nearly a decade largely because my strengths have been better suited to steep & technical trail races like @Transvulcaniabyutmb (May), so that's where I raced

Unfortunately, at around mile 4 a little off camber slip in the mud gave me the mild strain in the groin that would keep me from continuing my mission to race with a lot of the best in our country over the full course 

It has been a long 2 years of recovering & building after my ACL/Meniscus surgery.  Incredibly, my knee doesn't give me ANY problems, but it has been a real journey (on-going) to return my surgery leg to full strength.  In the last few weeks of training leading up to Lake Sononma 50 mile, I was happy to see some substantial fitness & strength gains just in time for the race. Well, that fitness is still here, the groin is 100% & I get to apply that fitness to more training & then racing at @lavaredoultratrail 80k in June... then @utmbmontblanc 

Time to party, not pout! 

I described how the new earned fitness feels to my coach, @mountainroche as "the difference between driving around on the trail in a clunky old truck vs a dirt bike, now I'm ready to get on a crotch rocket dirt bike!"

Fantastic 📷 @shitinthewoods

New fueling strategy for training: fuel almost every run w/ @spring_energy 

In the past, I've only fueled when the run is longer than 2hrs. I felt this strategy helped me become more efficient at metabolizing & using fat as fuel & be less reliant on carbs

In the past, it was fun to chase minimalism & become less reliant on having to have as much fuel & even water. If you weren't there, it was all the rage back in 2008-2016. Tony, Joe, Geoff, Killian & company championing the minimalist fuel/water strategy 

I've seen the benefits of racing both personally & with my coaching clients at the 250-350cal/hr (50-100gr carbs/hr). Now, I am experimenting to see if more carb fueling on most all my training runs (over 45min) will improve gut adaptation, reduce gastrointestinal distress in my racing & if I see improved recovery

Excited to see what I discover!

I strongly believe in always being open to change & learning. Food/fuel choices isn't a religion or some special club I need to be loyal to ❤️🙏! 

Keep learning & growing!

💥Experiment Continues w/ Workout Wed:
♤Adding fuel @spring_energy (45g carb) after warming up before my hard effort run♤ 
This is a personal experiment, but I have been running hard workouts, well, since the mid 90s, so I know how my body normally feels before, during & after. 
So far I can tell a difference after a few weeks of this change in that I feel less "bonking" sensations on the cool down & after finishing. 
In the past, I've embraced the post hard workout bonk feel as a badge of honor. Feeling good & recovering well/better with fuel is a better badge of honor 🎖

Here is what happened...

1) I didn't get my surgery leg as strong as my non-surgery leg
2) Non-surgery leg got some tendonitis from overuse 
3) I overdid my alt training & favored/overworked my surgery leg
4) My surgery leg's medial meniscus took the hit & a "hang nail" piece of meniscus started to catch (HORRIBLE feeling)

Like a big low point in an ultramarathon or in life, sometimes we just have to keep holding on. 
Keep showing up, problem solve, lean in on the love & the wisdom of others.  Believe & fight, fight, fight! 

This summer, I've been in the trenches of injury. I've missed races, I've had surgery, I thought I had a stress fracture & my legs have just been imbalanced.
I've never had to play the injury game in the past & I've had to adapt, learn & hardest of all, change. I've tried to cheat & skip to running big volume. I tried to cheat & not properly strengthen & fix imbalance. I just wanted to get back to racing well right away. 
Begrudgingly, I've gotten better at getting help, paying for help. Thank you @redefinephysio thank you Matt & Jenna at Mercy Orthopedis & thank you @mountainroche for encouraging me to treat myself like a professional athlete & get professional help. 

Relief. Racing & running in wilderness mountain terrain isn't everything, but it IS my passion. This week, I've finally been able to run with strength, without pain, with much improved balance & I got to do a workout on the trails. Last weekend, I told Felix while we were on a big backing trip, "left leg is back!"

I've held on, I've fought, I've learned.  I'm at the next aid station & I'm going to the next!

When I got home Monday night from UTMB, my week included two no sleep travel days, an all-nighter crewing TDS, 4hrs sleeping for UTMB & I did my biggest & only consistent running week in months... time for 5 x 3 min hills in the morning & then @devil_on_the_divide 50k on Saturday
DOtD avg elevation is over 11,000ft 3,352m, goes to 13,200ft 4,023m over very technical trails... with miles of off trail 😳

REWIND: 
July, I couldn't run more than 3 miles without my knee locking up. Fear consumed me & thoughts I may never run in the mountains again plagued me. Meniscus "hangnail" trim surgery & I was back to training

-August, I believed I had a stress fracture on my fibula. Luckily, David insisted on an MRI that found no stress fracture. It was tendonitis.

-The week leading up to UTMB I was able to get some consistent running. The week of UTMB, inspired by my athletes & Norda 665, I enjoyed a week of steep mountain running to include a 22m run with 6.5k climbing

The possibility of running @devil_on_the_divide
50k seemed... possible. Outrageous, but possible. 
I don't feel 45, I AM 25 💥

"Remember the goal is not to do the fastest time you possibly can, it's to have a fully embodied mountain experience. Let's aim for prescene every step and to soak it all in!!!!" 
@mountainroche
First reaction: I'm going to win no matter what & run faster than what is possible: 25. 
45 me, I am going to execute perfectly while smiling in the alpine!

I loaded the @ultimatedirection Schlarb Shorts with:
-350cal with 90carbs per hour for 4 hrs (no calories for first hour) of @spring_energy Awesome Sauce, Cannaberry & Ginger Orange Endurance Juice Mix. 
-1 dose of Naproxen to take at 3hrs
-290mg of caffeine to be taken incrementally 3:20, 3:30, 3:40
-1 electrolyte drink mix to be taken in the 2nd half
- @nordarun 001 on my feet! 

I ran this race super steady, which resulted in my heart rate staying fairly close to my 155 avg until the final 5 miles of descent when it was party time

I smiled all day & embodied the mountain experience at one of the most beautiful high alpine point-to -point mountain 50ks. 

I ran 4:56 for the 🥇 & 8th all-time (3 min away from 5th)

📸 @jchapell

Today was the last golden day, Reunion 🇷🇪 tomorrow!

#GrandRaide #LaDiagonaleDesFous

Courage, belief & a bit of blind faith is what I clung to as I faced a second knee surgery in July followed by news of a stress fracture a few weeks later. 

Thankfully, there was no stress fracture & I was able to start workouts on the elliptiGo, bike & do some running the same week of the surgery. 

September couldn't have been more different than July. After some time in Chamonix with Norda 665, my athletes, Whitney & a good week of training, I raced & won @devil_on_the_divide 50k in Colorado 5 days after getting back from Cham. I've been able to put together three weeks of 80+ miles in a row along with directing @the_run_beyond_experience Sky Island 50k, Durango Fall Classic & commentary at @runrabbitrun100 

While it has been 3 very crazy months, I'm ready to celebrate by racing @grandraidreunion 100m on the 19th of October 🙏🏽

#UltimateDirection #SchlarbShorts

Today, Emanuel guided me around his home trails in St Leu, La Reunion 🇷🇪 

This run adventure with Emanuel made the whole trip worth it. While seeing new trails on Reunion Island is wonderful, sharing the experience with someone who lives here & passionately calls this place home is priceless. Emanuel genuinely loves & appreciates the trails, wildlife, flora, the ocean, the mountains, the people & all the components that make up the wild places in his backyard. 

Thank you, Emanuel, for a run I will never forget & that brought me so much joy 🙏🏽

I promised myself 9 years ago that I would return to @grandraidreunion & run Diagonal des Fous 100 mile

As you can see in the 1st picture, Grand Raid destroyed me.  It was the first & only time I've ever been so exhausted that I have had hallucinations

The day before I raced & won @hardrock100run in 2016, I reflected back to Grand Raide & wrote: 
"As #hardrock100 draws near with all the excitement, hype, expectations & fears, I try to remember why I'm here. Why I do this. Why? 
To adventure, test, strip away everything until I find myself in the raw, exposed, & wild places of my mind & our planet. I am ready."

I am proud to say I am ready for all of this once again.

A day in Munich on our way to race @himamtrailrun in Oman 🇴🇲

Oman 🇴🇲 
Snorkeling with sea turtles, sea eagles soaring over mountainous ocean shorelines, beautiful architecture everywhere, the Sultan's Palace, reuniting with friends @hamedalharthy1 and @assimalsaqri 🙏🏽
Day 2 was so good.

Day 3 🇴🇲

The Grand Mosque, @himamtrailrun race check in, time with new and old friends 🙏🏽

Day 4 🇴🇲
Easy run around Nizwah, water park fun, chill & get ready for @himamtrailrun 114k in the morning!

Thank you Oman 🇴🇲 

@himamtrailrun 114k/5,700m is the toughest & most technical race I've ever raced & I love it ❤️
I'm so proud to return to Oman & be able to race to a🥈finish 

My race was full of unique challenges. I ran the first 2,000m climb without my Leki pole straps. In the lead, I got lost (my fault) for half an hour & the biggest challenge of the race was my stomach rejecting nutrition & hydration for the last 6hrs

Our capacity to persevere is incredible. This is one of my favorite parts of our trail running sport & I really got to see what I could do in a tough situation here in Oman

The Omani volunteers, fans & race organizers kept me going along with having Whitney & Felix supporting me 

Himam, which means courage & boldness, was one of the most gratifying race experiences of my life 

Thank you all 🙏🏽

Wadi Worriers 

The last 20km of the 114km (Jason’s race) and the 55km (my race) have the same finish. @himamtrailrun 

Lucky for me, I received great advice from Jason about the finish because on the elevation profile, it just looks like a down hill finish to the end, but in reality it is more like Canyoneering down a trail-less canyon/wadi for almost 10km. You loose a fast 1,680 feet on a dirt road and then drop down into a wadi. 

Jason warned me to save my legs for this section. It is trail-less most of the time and has a lot of scrambling down and around the wadi. 

Even with Jason’s advice, it was super challenging, but so fun! 

The canyons/wadis in Oman are so spectacular. Yesterday I was glad we got to walk slowly and explore a different wadi but very similar to the one we race in. 

The wadi was so wonderful that we could not resist running out and racing the Land Rover 🤣 
we also saw 33 frogs 🥳

Hunting

Chasing 1st place, unable to eat or drink & enduring dry heaves created a special experience at @himamtrailrun 

Felix, Whitney & so many enthusiastic Omani fans kept me going. I never gave up the hunt for 1st & furthermore,  the hunt to be as fast as I possibly can. 

Never ever quit!!
Omani Camel 🐫 transporter

After the race, Whitney, Felix & I got to explore a beautiful wadi. With only our leftover @spring_energy we spent the entire day exploring. It's nice to have easy real food in a pinch

Enjoy exploring ✨️

Competion & commraderie are two aspects of sport I cherish. 
Rather you are winning, in the middle of the pack, or chasing cut-offs, I hope you appreciate the competition & I hope it leads to great memories & friendship 

Congratulations to @hamdanrunning
on a great victory at @himamtrailrun 114k. I had a great time racing with you 🙏🏽

📸 @a.baluchi

My third trip to Oman 🇴🇲 did not disappoint. Each trip to Oman has been amazing.  The incredible landscapes have been so beautiful. The rugged mountains, the beautiful ocean & underwater ecosystems & my favorite: water filled wadis (canyons) of magnificent limestone

After a beautiful race, we are already planning on returning to Oman for @himamtrailrun in 2024 

📸 @running_midwife_whit

It's great to see the @himamtrailrun race organization value both growing this trail race locally and internationally. Himam invited and supported professionals trail runners from around the world at their event

The support at Himam included an impressive prize purse for multiple races over the weekend
1,100 Oman Riyal = $2,855 USD 

Himam also put on 3 KIDS races with HUNDEREDS of kids participating. 200 kids were in the 8-10 year old 2k race!! Felix's race (2nd photo) had over a hundred kids in the race as well ❤️

Himam builds so much trail community 🙏🏽
